   Unfortunately not. For example, if I change the signatures to their generic form like this:
   ```typescript
       public static from<T extends Int>(this: typeof IntVector, input: T['TArray']): V<T>;
       public static from<T extends Int>(this: typeof IntVector, input: BigInt64Array): V<T>;
       public static from<T extends Int>(this: typeof IntVector, input: BigUint64Array): V<T>;
       public static from<T extends Int>(this: typeof IntVector, input: T['TArray'], is64bit: true): V<T>;
       public static from<T extends Int>(this: typeof IntVector, input: T['TArray'], is64bit: true): V<T>;
   ```
   
   it causes the "test strong typing at compile-time" tests [here](https://github.com/apache/arrow/pull/4746/files/2a6691305ed2fb1eeff90a0286992e39fa04d967#diff-a92b06b2ed35319c47a86b2b08d0947cR231) to throw a compiler error. It seems like TS will only infer the argument type from the generic, and not the generic type from the argument:
   
